  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is chaga mushroom and what are its benefits?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Chaga (Inonotus obliquus) is a parasitic fungus that grows on birch trees in cold northern climates including Siberia, Northern Canada, and Scandinavia. It has been used in Russian and Scandinavian folk medicine for centuries as an immune tonic and general health promoter. Chaga contains one of the highest concentrations of antioxidants found in any natural substance, with an ORAC (Oxygen Radical Absorbance Capacity) score of 146,700 — higher than acai berries, blueberries, or any other superfood. Its primary bioactive compounds include beta-glucan polysaccharides for immune modulation, melanin for antioxidant protection, betulinic acid from birch bark for anti-inflammatory effects, and superoxide dismutase (SOD) for cellular protection.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How does chaga support the immune system?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Chaga\'s immune-supporting properties come primarily from its beta-glucan polysaccharides, which interact with receptors on immune cells (primarily Dectin-1 and Complement Receptor 3) to modulate immune function. Unlike immune stimulants that push the immune system into overdrive, beta-glucans act as biological response modifiers — they upregulate underactive immune responses and can help regulate overactive ones. Research published in the International Journal of Biological Macromolecules found that chaga polysaccharides activated macrophages and increased the production of cytokines including IL-6 and TNF-alpha. This immunomodulatory (rather than purely immunostimulatory) effect makes chaga appropriate for ongoing use.' } },
